(45, 1, 1, 24, 1, 5, 5, 'separated unto the gospel of God', 'Divine Calling and Sanctification', 'This connection highlights the theme of being called and sanctified for a specific purpose. Both Paul and Jeremiah are depicted as chosen individuals, set apart for God''s mission.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 1, 51, 1, 1, 1, 'called to be an apostle', 'Connection of Apostolic Authority', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s role as an apostle of Jesus Christ. The phrase ''apostle of Jesus Christ'' in Colossians directly connects to Paul''s identity in Romans.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 1, 56, 1, 1, 1, 'a servant of Jesus Christ', 'Connection of Apostolic Identity', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s role as a servant and apostle, highlighting his dedication to the gospel and the faith of believers. This connection underscores the continuity of his mission in spreading the message of Jesus Christ.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 1, 45, 1, 9, 9, 'gospel of God', 'Connection of Service in Gospel', 'Both passages emphasize serving in the gospel. Romans 1:1 mentions being ''separated unto the gospel of God,'' while Romans 1:9 speaks of serving ''in the gospel of his Son.'' This connection highlights the commitment to the gospel in Paul''s ministry.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 2, 56, 1, 2, 2, 'promised afore by his prophets', 'Promise of Eternal Life', 'Both passages emphasize God''s promise, with Romans referencing the prophets and Titus highlighting the eternal life promised before time. This connection highlights the continuity of God''s promises throughout scripture.', 'theme', 0.496, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 2, 42, 1, 70, 70, 'by his prophets in the holy scriptures', 'Connection of Prophetic Promises', 'Both passages emphasize the role of prophets in conveying God''s promises. Romans highlights the prophetic nature of the scriptures, while Luke notes that these prophets have spoken since the world''s beginning.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 2, 45, 3, 21, 21, 'by his prophets in the holy scriptures', 'Connection of Prophetic Witness', 'This connection highlights the role of the prophets in affirming God''s righteousness. Both passages emphasize the prophetic witness to God''s promises and righteousness as revealed in the scriptures.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 2, 45, 16, 26, 26, 'by his prophets in the holy scriptures', 'Connection of Prophetic Scriptures', 'Both passages emphasize the role of ''the scriptures of the prophets'' in revealing God''s plan. Romans 1:2 mentions the promise made by prophets, while Romans 16:26 highlights its manifestation through those same scriptures.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 2, 44, 10, 43, 43, 'by his prophets in the holy scriptures', 'Prophetic Witness of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the role of prophets in affirming the message of Jesus. Both passages emphasize the prophetic witness regarding salvation through faith in Him.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 2, 42, 24, 26, 27, 'promised afore by his prophets', 'Connection of Prophetic Fulfillment', 'This connection highlights the theme of prophecy, as both passages reference the fulfillment of what was promised by the prophets. Romans emphasizes the prior promises in the holy scriptures, while Luke illustrates how Christ''s suffering and glory were expounded from those same scriptures.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 2, 44, 26, 6, 6, NULL, 'Connection of God''s Promises', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of God''s promises. Romans 1:2 refers to promises made by prophets, while Acts 26:6 speaks of the hope of the promise made to the fathers.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 3, 40, 1, 1, 1, NULL, 'Connection of Jesus'' Davidic Lineage', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus as the ''son of David,'' highlighting his lineage. Romans 1:3 refers to Jesus being made of the seed of David, while Matthew 1:1 explicitly states he is the son of David.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 3, 48, 4, 4, 4, 'made of the seed of David', 'Connection of Jesus'' Humanity', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus Christ''s human lineage and origin. Romans highlights his descent from David, while Galatians notes he was ''made of a woman,'' underscoring his human nature.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 3, 24, 23, 5, 6, 'seed of David', 'Connection of Davidic Lineage', 'Both passages emphasize the lineage of David, with Romans referencing Jesus as ''made of the seed of David'' and Jeremiah prophesying a ''righteous Branch'' from David. This highlights the fulfillment of the promise of a king from David''s line.', 'prophecy', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 3, 43, 1, 14, 14, 'made of the seed of David', 'Connection of Jesus'' Humanity', 'This connection highlights the incarnation of Jesus, as both passages emphasize his being made flesh. Romans 1:3 refers to Jesus being made of the seed of David, while John 1:14 states that the Word was made flesh.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 3, 40, 1, 20, 23, 'seed of David according to the flesh', 'Connection of Davidic Lineage', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' lineage from David, highlighting his fulfillment of messianic prophecy. Romans states he was ''made of the seed of David,'' while Matthew identifies Joseph as ''thou son of David,'' linking their genealogies.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 3, 42, 1, 31, 33, 'seed of David', 'Connection of Jesus and David', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' lineage from David. Romans highlights Jesus as ''the seed of David,'' while Luke states he will inherit ''the throne of his father David.'' This connection underscores the fulfillment of messianic expectations.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 3, 23, 9, 6, 7, 'made of the seed of David', 'Connection of Davidic Lineage', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of Jesus'' lineage from David. Romans 1:3 states he was ''made of the seed of David,'' while Isaiah 9:7 refers to his reign ''upon the throne of David.'' This highlights the fulfillment of the Davidic promise.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 4, 58, 9, 14, 14, 'according to the spirit of holiness', 'Connection of Christ''s Sacrifice', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Spirit in Christ''s offering and resurrection. Romans highlights the power of the resurrection, while Hebrews speaks of Christ offering himself through the Spirit, linking the themes of divine empowerment and sacrificial atonement.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 4, 49, 1, 19, 23, 'by the resurrection from the dead', 'Resurrection and Divine Power', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine power demonstrated through Christ''s resurrection. Both passages emphasize the significance of the resurrection in establishing Christ''s authority and position in the heavenly realm.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 4, 58, 5, 5, 6, NULL, 'Connection of Sonship and Priesthood', 'This connection highlights the declaration of Jesus as the Son of God in Romans, which is echoed in Hebrews where God affirms Jesus'' sonship and priestly role. Both passages emphasize the significance of Jesus'' identity and authority in relation to his divine appointment.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 4, 44, 13, 33, 35, 'Son of God with power', 'Resurrection and Sonship Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the resurrection of Jesus as a declaration of His identity as the Son of God. Romans 1:4 states He was declared the Son of God by the resurrection, while Acts 13:33 references Psalm 2, affirming His sonship through resurrection.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 4, 47, 13, 4, 4, NULL, 'Power of God in Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the power of God in relation to Jesus'' resurrection and life. Romans highlights Jesus being declared the Son of God by the resurrection, while 2 Corinthians speaks of living by the power of God, linking the themes of divine strength and resurrection.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 4, 43, 2, 18, 21, 'by the resurrection from the dead', 'Resurrection and Jesus'' Body', 'This connection highlights the theme of resurrection in both passages. Romans 1:4 speaks of Jesus being declared the Son of God by the resurrection, while John 2:19 refers to Jesus raising his body after death, linking the two through the concept of resurrection.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 4, 44, 5, 30, 32, 'declared to be the Son of God', 'Resurrection and Exaltation of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' resurrection and exaltation. Both passages affirm that God raised Jesus and declared him as the Son of God with power, emphasizing his role as Savior.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 1, 5, 44, 9, 15, 15, 'for his name', 'Connection of Apostleship and Mission', 'Both passages emphasize the mission to bear God''s name among the nations. Romans 1:5 speaks of apostleship for obedience to faith, while Acts 9:15 highlights being a chosen vessel to bear His name before the Gentiles.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
