(45, 2, 14, 44, 10, 35, 35, NULL, 'Acceptance of Righteousness Across Nations', 'Both passages emphasize that individuals who act righteously, regardless of their knowledge of the law, are accepted by God. Romans highlights that Gentiles can be a ''law unto themselves,'' while Acts states that those who ''worketh righteousness'' are accepted in every nation.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 2, 14, 49, 2, 12, 12, 'having not the law', 'Gentiles and Their Relationship to Law', 'Both passages emphasize the status of Gentiles in relation to God''s law and promises. Romans 2:14 highlights Gentiles acting as a law unto themselves, while Ephesians 2:12 describes them as strangers from the covenants of promise.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 2, 14, 5, 4, 7, 7, NULL, 'God''s Presence Among Nations', 'This connection highlights the idea of nations having a unique relationship with God. Romans 2:14 suggests that Gentiles can embody God''s law naturally, while Deuteronomy 4:7 emphasizes the closeness of God to His people, indicating a universal aspect of divine presence.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 2, 15, 47, 5, 11, 11, 'their conscience also bearing witness', 'Conscience and Persuasion Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of conscience in human behavior. Romans discusses the conscience bearing witness, while 2 Corinthians highlights being manifest in consciences, linking the internal moral awareness to the act of persuasion.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 2, 15, 45, 1, 18, 19, 'the work of the law written in their hearts', 'Connection of Conscience and Truth', 'Both passages emphasize the internal awareness of God''s truth. Romans 2:15 speaks of the law written in hearts, while Romans 1:19 discusses how God''s truth is manifest in them.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 2, 15, 47, 1, 12, 12, 'conscience also bearing witness', 'Conscience as Witness', 'This connection highlights the role of conscience in both passages. Romans discusses the conscience bearing witness to the law, while 2 Corinthians emphasizes the testimony of the conscience in the believer''s conduct.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 2, 15, 56, 1, 15, 15, 'their conscience also bearing witness', 'Conscience and Purity Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of conscience in determining purity and moral judgment. Romans highlights the conscience bearing witness, while Titus states that the defiled conscience leads to a lack of purity.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
