(45, 3, 7, 45, 9, 19, 20, 'why yet am I also judged as a sinner?', 'Divine Sovereignty and Human Response', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between God''s will and human actions. Romans 3:7 questions the judgment of a sinner in light of God''s truth, while Romans 9:19-20 addresses human accountability in response to God''s sovereignty.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 3, 7, 44, 13, 27, 29, 'judged as a sinner', 'Fulfillment of Prophecy and Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment in both passages. Romans discusses being judged as a sinner, while Acts describes the rulers'' judgment of Jesus despite finding no cause for death.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 3, 7, 12, 8, 10, 15, NULL, 'Judgment and Deception Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of judgment in the context of deception. In Romans, the speaker questions why they are judged as a sinner despite the truth of God being revealed through their lie, while in 2 Kings, Hazael deceives his master about his intentions, leading to judgment against Israel.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 3, 7, 23, 10, 6, 7, 'judged as a sinner', 'Judgment and Divine Purpose', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment and the role of individuals in executing God''s purposes. Both passages emphasize the idea of being judged despite a greater divine intention, as seen in the ''hypocritical nation'' and the ''sinner.''', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 3, 7, 40, 26, 34, 34, 'judged as a sinner', 'Denial and Judgment Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment in both passages. In Romans, the speaker questions why they are judged as a sinner despite the truth of God being revealed, while in Matthew, Jesus predicts Peter''s denial, which leads to his judgment.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 3, 7, 40, 26, 69, 75, 'I also judged as a sinner', 'Denial and Judgment Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of denial and judgment. In Romans, the speaker questions why they are judged as a sinner despite the truth of God being glorified, while in Matthew, Peter''s denial of Jesus leads to his own judgment and remorse.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 3, 8, 45, 6, 1, 1, 'that good may come', 'Connection of Sin and Grace', 'Both passages emphasize the question of continuing in sin to achieve a greater good, specifically regarding grace. The phrase ''that good may come'' in Romans 3:8 parallels the inquiry in Romans 6:1 about whether grace can abound through sin.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 3, 8, 45, 6, 15, 15, 'Let us do evil, that good may come?', 'Connection on Sin and Grace', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between sin and the concept of grace. Romans 3:8 addresses the misuse of grace to justify sin, while Romans 6:15 questions the idea of sinning under grace, reinforcing the need for moral responsibility.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 3, 8, 60, 3, 16, 17, 'slanderously reported', 'Connection of Suffering for Good', 'This connection highlights the theme of being falsely accused for doing good. Both passages emphasize that suffering for righteousness is preferable to suffering for wrongdoing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 3, 8, 65, 1, 4, 4, 'Let us do evil, that good may come?', 'Connection of Grace and Condemnation', 'Both passages emphasize the misuse of grace, where individuals distort it for immoral purposes. Romans warns against the idea of doing evil for good outcomes, while Jude addresses those who turn grace into lasciviousness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 3, 8, 40, 5, 11, 11, NULL, 'Reviling and False Accusations', 'This connection highlights the theme of being falsely accused and reviled for righteousness. Both passages address the experience of slander and the unjust treatment of believers, emphasizing the response to such persecution.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 3, 9, 48, 3, 22, 22, 'that they are all under sin', 'Universal Sinfulness Theme', 'Both passages emphasize that all are ''under sin,'' highlighting the universal condition of humanity. This shared theme underscores the need for faith in Jesus Christ for salvation.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 3, 9, 45, 6, 15, 15, 'under sin', 'Sin and Grace Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the condition of being under sin and the implications of grace. The first verse establishes that all are under sin, while the second addresses the question of sinning under grace, highlighting the moral responsibility that comes with it.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 3, 9, 23, 65, 5, 5, 'all under sin', 'Sin and Self-Righteousness', 'Both passages emphasize the universal condition of sinfulness. Romans highlights that all, including Jews and Gentiles, are under sin, while Isaiah critiques those who consider themselves holier than others, indicating a false sense of righteousness.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 3, 9, 45, 3, 22, 23, 'for we have before proved both Jews and Gentiles, that they are all under sin', 'Connection of Sin and Righteousness', 'Both passages emphasize that ''all'' are under sin, highlighting the universality of sinfulness among Jews and Gentiles. This sets the stage for the need for the righteousness of God through faith in Jesus Christ.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 3, 9, 42, 7, 39, 39, 'all under sin', 'Connection of Sinfulness Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the universality of sin. Romans states that both Jews and Gentiles are ''under sin,'' while Luke highlights a specific sinner, illustrating that all are in need of grace.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
