(45, 9, 19, 18, 9, 19, 19, NULL, 'Divine Authority and Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine authority in both passages. Romans questions human resistance to God''s will, while Job acknowledges God''s strength and authority in judgment.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 20, 23, 29, 16, 16, 'the thing formed say to him that formed it', 'Potter and Clay Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between the creator and the created, questioning the right of the creation to challenge its maker. The imagery of the potter and clay serves to illustrate the authority of God over humanity.', 'theme', 0.482, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 20, 23, 45, 9, 11, 'Shall the thing formed say to him that formed it', 'Striving with the Maker', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between the Creator and the created, warning against questioning God''s intentions. The imagery of clay and potsherds in Isaiah parallels the idea of the formed questioning the one who formed it in Romans.', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 20, 18, 33, 13, 13, 'Why hast thou made me thus?', 'Divine Authority and Human Response', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between God and humanity, questioning the validity of human objections to divine actions. They highlight the idea that humans should not challenge God''s decisions or purposes.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 20, 18, 40, 2, 2, NULL, 'Contending with God', 'This connection highlights the theme of questioning God''s authority. Both passages emphasize the futility of contending with the Almighty and challenge the created to question their Creator.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 20, 40, 20, 15, 15, 'Why hast thou made me thus?', 'Divine Authority and Goodness', 'Both passages emphasize God''s authority over creation and His right to act according to His goodness. Romans 9:20 questions the created''s right to question the Creator, while Matthew 20:15 asserts God''s freedom to do as He pleases. This connection highlights the theme of divine sovereignty.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 20, 46, 1, 20, 20, 'Why hast thou made me thus?', 'Divine Wisdom vs. Human Understanding', 'This connection highlights the theme of human limitations in understanding God''s purposes. Both passages emphasize the folly of questioning God''s design and wisdom, illustrating the contrast between divine intention and human reasoning.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 20, 54, 6, 5, 5, 'Why hast thou made me thus?', 'Disputing Against God', 'This connection highlights the theme of questioning God''s authority. Both passages emphasize the folly of humans disputing or arguing against divine intentions, suggesting a lack of understanding or truth.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 21, 23, 64, 8, 8, 'the potter power over the clay', 'Potter and Clay Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between the potter and the clay, illustrating God''s sovereignty in shaping individuals for different purposes. Romans 9:21 reflects this theme by discussing vessels of honor and dishonor, while Isaiah 64:8 explicitly identifies God as the potter and humanity as the clay.', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 21, 20, 16, 4, 4, 'the potter power over the clay', 'Divine Sovereignty Over Creation', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s authority in shaping creation. Both passages emphasize that God has the power to create vessels for different purposes, including the wicked for specific outcomes.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 21, 55, 2, 20, 21, 'vessel unto honour, and another unto dishonour', 'Vessels of Honor and Dishonor', 'Both passages emphasize the distinction between vessels of honor and dishonor. Romans 9:21 speaks of the potter''s authority to make different vessels, while 2 Timothy 2:20-21 elaborates on the types of vessels in a great house, linking them to honor and dishonor.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 21, 24, 18, 3, 6, 'the potter power over the clay', 'Potter and Clay Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between the potter and the clay, illustrating God''s sovereignty over His creation. Romans 9:21 reflects the idea of making vessels for different purposes, while Jeremiah 18:3-6 depicts the potter reshaping the clay as he sees fit.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 21, 44, 9, 15, 15, 'vessel unto honour, and another unto dishonour', 'Connection of Vessels in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of vessels, with Romans discussing the potter''s authority to create vessels for different purposes, while Acts identifies a specific individual as a chosen vessel for God''s mission. This connection highlights the theme of divine selection and purpose.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 21, 45, 9, 22, 23, 'the potter power over the clay', 'Connection of Divine Sovereignty', 'This connection highlights God''s authority as the potter over the clay, illustrating His ability to create both vessels of honor and vessels of wrath. Both passages emphasize the purpose behind God''s creations, whether for mercy or destruction.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 21, 45, 9, 11, 11, NULL, 'Divine Sovereignty in Creation', 'Both passages emphasize God''s authority in determining the roles of individuals. Romans 9:21 illustrates the potter''s power over the clay, while Romans 9:11 discusses God''s purpose in election, highlighting His control over outcomes regardless of human actions.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 22, 20, 16, 4, 4, 'vessels of wrath fitted to destruction', 'Connection of Divine Purpose', 'Both passages emphasize God''s sovereignty over all creation, including the wicked. Romans 9:22 speaks of vessels of wrath, while Proverbs 16:4 states that even the wicked are made for a purpose.', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 22, 65, 1, 4, 4, 'vessels of wrath fitted to destruction', 'Connection of Wrath and Condemnation', 'Both passages emphasize God''s judgment and the fate of the ungodly. Romans discusses vessels of wrath fitted to destruction, while Jude refers to men ordained to condemnation, highlighting a theme of divine retribution.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 22, 45, 9, 21, 21, 'vessels of wrath fitted to destruction', 'Connection of Potter and Vessels', 'Both passages emphasize God''s authority over creation, illustrating how He can shape vessels for different purposes. The concept of ''vessels'' in both verses highlights the distinction between those made for honor and those for dishonor.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 22, 60, 2, 8, 8, 'vessels of wrath fitted to destruction', 'Connection of Wrath and Disobedience', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of disobedience, with Romans highlighting God''s wrath towards ''vessels of wrath'' and 1 Peter referencing those who ''stumble at the word'' due to disobedience. This connection highlights the theme of divine judgment against those who reject God''s message.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 22, 55, 2, 20, 20, 'vessels of wrath fitted to destruction', 'Vessels of Wrath and Honor', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''vessels'' in relation to honor and dishonor. Romans discusses ''vessels of wrath fitted to destruction,'' while 2 Timothy contrasts vessels of honor and dishonor, highlighting the differing purposes of these vessels.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 22, 2, 9, 16, 16, NULL, 'God''s Power and Purpose', 'This connection highlights God''s intention to demonstrate His power through specific individuals. Both passages emphasize the idea of God raising up vessels to showcase His might and declare His name.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 22, 52, 2, 16, 16, 'his wrath', 'Connection of God''s Wrath', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s wrath against those who oppose His will. Both passages emphasize the consequences of sin and the enduring nature of God''s judgment.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 23, 45, 2, 4, 4, 'riches of his glory', 'Riches of God''s Goodness', 'Both passages emphasize the ''riches'' of God, highlighting His mercy and goodness. Romans 9:23 refers to the ''riches of his glory,'' while Romans 2:4 speaks of the ''riches of his goodness,'' suggesting a thematic link in understanding God''s character.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 23, 60, 1, 2, 5, 'vessels of mercy', 'Connection of Mercy and Hope', 'Both passages emphasize God''s mercy and preparation for glory. Romans speaks of ''vessels of mercy,'' while 1 Peter highlights being ''begotten... unto a lively hope'' through God''s mercy.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 23, 45, 5, 20, 21, 'vessels of mercy', 'Connection of Grace and Mercy', 'This connection highlights the theme of grace and mercy in both passages. Romans 9:23 speaks of ''vessels of mercy,'' while Romans 5:20-21 emphasizes how grace abounds even more than sin, illustrating God''s intention to showcase His glory through mercy.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 23, 49, 2, 10, 10, NULL, 'Vessels of Mercy and Workmanship', 'This connection highlights the idea of being ''prepared'' or ''ordained'' for a purpose. Both passages emphasize that God has a plan for those He has chosen, whether as vessels of mercy or as His workmanship.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 23, 49, 3, 16, 16, 'riches of his glory', 'Connection of Divine Riches', 'Both passages emphasize the ''riches of his glory.'' Romans speaks of these riches in relation to vessels of mercy, while Ephesians connects them to spiritual strength. This connection highlights the theme of God''s glory manifesting in believers.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 23, 51, 1, 27, 27, 'riches of his glory', 'Riches of Glory Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the ''riches of glory'' in relation to God''s purpose. Romans speaks of vessels of mercy prepared for glory, while Colossians reveals this glory as a mystery among the Gentiles through Christ.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 23, 13, 29, 18, 18, 'prepared unto glory', 'Preparation of Hearts and Glory', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of preparation, with Romans highlighting God''s preparation of vessels for glory and 1 Chronicles calling for the preparation of hearts towards God. This connection highlights the importance of being ready to receive divine mercy and glory.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 24, 51, 3, 11, 11, 'not of the Jews only, but also of the Gentiles', 'Unity in Christ Across Cultures', 'Both passages emphasize the inclusion of Gentiles alongside Jews in God''s calling. They highlight the breaking down of cultural and social barriers, asserting that in Christ, all distinctions are transcended.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 24, 1, 49, 10, 10, NULL, 'Connection of Calling and Gathering', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s call to both Jews and Gentiles, as seen in Romans 9:24, and the gathering of people referenced in Genesis 49:10. Both passages emphasize a divine purpose in uniting diverse groups under God''s plan.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 24, 19, 22, 27, 27, 'not of the Jews only, but also of the Gentiles', 'Inclusivity of God''s Call', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s call extending beyond the Jews to include the Gentiles. Both passages emphasize that all nations and kindreds will turn to and worship the Lord.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 24, 44, 13, 47, 48, 'also of the Gentiles', 'Connection of Gentile Salvation', 'Both passages emphasize the inclusion of Gentiles in God''s plan for salvation. Romans 9:24 mentions the calling of Gentiles, while Acts 13:47-48 highlights their response to this message.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 24, 44, 15, 14, 14, 'also of the Gentiles', 'God''s Call to Gentiles', 'Both passages emphasize God''s initiative to include Gentiles in His plan. Romans 9:24 mentions the calling of Gentiles, while Acts 15:14 describes God''s visit to Gentiles to form a people for His name.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 24, 45, 3, 29, 30, 'not of the Jews only, but also of the Gentiles', 'Connection of God''s Inclusivity', 'Both passages emphasize that God is not limited to the Jews but also includes the Gentiles in His plan of justification. This connection highlights the universal scope of God''s call and justification through faith.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 24, 45, 8, 28, 30, NULL, 'Calling of the Gentiles', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being ''called'' by God. Romans 9:24 highlights that this calling extends beyond the Jews to the Gentiles, while Romans 8:28-30 discusses those who are called according to God''s purpose, indicating a broader inclusion.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 25, 28, 2, 23, 23, 'which were not my people', 'Connection of People and Mercy', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of calling those who were not considered God''s people and extending mercy to them. This connection highlights the transformation of identity and relationship with God.', 'theme', 0.489, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 25, 60, 2, 10, 10, 'which were not my people', 'Connection of People and Mercy', 'Both passages emphasize the transformation of identity for those who were previously excluded. They highlight the shift from being ''not a people'' to becoming ''the people of God'' and the reception of mercy.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 25, 26, 16, 8, 8, 'my people', 'Covenant and Belonging', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of God establishing a relationship with those who were previously excluded. Romans 9:25 refers to calling ''my people,'' while Ezekiel 16:8 describes entering into a covenant, indicating a shift in identity and belonging.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 25, 43, 16, 27, 27, NULL, 'Love and Belonging in Faith', 'This connection highlights the theme of belonging and love. In Romans, God calls those who were not His people, while in John, the Father loves those who believe in Jesus, emphasizing inclusion and acceptance.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 25, 45, 1, 7, 7, 'beloved', 'Connection of Beloved and Called', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being ''beloved'' and ''called.'' Romans 9:25 speaks of those who were not considered God''s people being called beloved, while Romans 1:7 addresses those in Rome as ''beloved of God, called to be saints.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 25, 28, 1, 1, 2, 'my people, which were not my people', 'Connection of People and Beloved', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s relationship with those who were previously rejected. Both passages emphasize the transformation of identity for those considered ''not my people'' and ''not beloved.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 26, 28, 1, 9, 10, 'Ye are not my people', 'Connection of Identity and Reclamation', 'Both passages emphasize the transition from rejection to acceptance as God''s people. The phrase ''Ye are not my people'' in Hosea is directly echoed in Romans, highlighting the fulfillment of God''s promise to reclaim those previously estranged.', 'quotation', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 26, 62, 3, 1, 3, 'Ye are not my people', 'Identity as Children of God', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being called ''children of God.'' Romans 9:26 speaks of those previously rejected being recognized as God''s people, while 1 John 3:1-3 affirms believers'' identity as sons of God, highlighting a transformative relationship with the divine.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 26, 23, 43, 6, 6, 'Ye are not my people', 'Children of God and Gathering', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s people being called and gathered. Both passages emphasize the transformation of identity, from being ''not my people'' to ''children of the living God'' and the call to bring ''my sons'' and ''daughters'' from afar.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 26, 45, 8, 16, 16, 'children of the living God', 'Children of God Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of identity as ''children of God'' in both passages. Romans 9:26 speaks of those who were once not recognized as God''s people being called His children, while Romans 8:16 affirms that believers are indeed recognized as children of God.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 26, 48, 3, 26, 26, 'children of the living God', 'Children of God Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of identity as children of God. Romans 9:26 speaks of being called ''children of the living God,'' while Galatians 3:26 states, ''ye are all the children of God.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 26, 47, 6, 18, 18, 'children of the living God', 'Connection of Divine Fatherhood', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of God claiming His people. Romans 9:26 speaks of being called ''children of the living God,'' while 2 Corinthians 6:18 directly states that believers will be His ''sons and daughters.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 26, 40, 16, 16, 16, 'the living God', 'Connection of Living God', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of the ''living God.'' Romans 9:26 speaks of God''s people being called ''children of the living God,'' while Matthew 16:16 identifies Jesus as ''the Son of the living God.'' This connection highlights the relationship between God and His people.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 27, 23, 10, 20, 23, 'a remnant shall be saved', 'Remnant of Israel Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a remnant of Israel being saved despite their large number. They highlight that, although Israel is numerous like the sand of the sea, only a remnant will return to God.', 'theme', 0.489, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 27, 45, 11, 4, 6, 'a remnant shall be saved', 'Remnant of Israel Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a remnant being saved from Israel. Romans 9:27 mentions a remnant, while Romans 11:4-6 discusses a remnant according to the election of grace.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 27, 23, 1, 9, 9, 'a remnant shall be saved', 'Remnant of Israel', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a ''remnant'' being saved from destruction. Romans 9:27 refers to a remnant of Israel, while Isaiah 1:9 speaks of a small remnant that was spared from judgment, highlighting God''s preservation of a faithful group.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 27, 28, 1, 10, 10, 'the number of the children of Israel be as the sand of the sea', 'Connection of Israel''s Remnant', 'Both passages emphasize the vast number of the children of Israel, likening them to ''the sand of the sea.'' However, Romans highlights that only a ''remnant shall be saved,'' indicating a selective preservation of Israel.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 27, 24, 5, 10, 10, 'a remnant shall be saved', 'Remnant and Destruction Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of a remnant being preserved amidst destruction. Romans highlights that a remnant shall be saved, while Jeremiah indicates that a full end will not be made, suggesting preservation in judgment.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 27, 26, 6, 8, 8, 'a remnant shall be saved', 'Remnant Theme in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a remnant being saved or escaping amidst judgment. Romans highlights a remnant of Israel, while Ezekiel speaks of a remnant that will escape the sword among the nations.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 27, 1, 22, 17, 17, 'the number of the children of Israel be as the sand of the sea', 'Remnant and Multiplication Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a large number of descendants, with Romans highlighting a remnant being saved from Israel, while Genesis speaks of multiplying the seed. This connection highlights the idea of a faithful remnant amidst a vast multitude.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 28, 23, 10, 23, 23, 'cut it short in righteousness', 'Divine Judgment and Righteousness', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a decisive action by God to bring about righteousness and judgment. Romans speaks of a ''short work'' in righteousness, while Isaiah refers to a ''consumption'' determined by God, indicating a swift and purposeful divine intervention.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 28, 23, 30, 12, 14, 'cut it short in righteousness', 'Judgment and Righteousness Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of divine judgment and the consequences of iniquity. Romans speaks of the Lord''s work in righteousness, while Isaiah warns of sudden destruction due to despising God''s word.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 28, 44, 17, 31, 31, 'cut it short in righteousness', 'Judgment and Righteousness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of righteousness in both passages. Romans 9:28 speaks of the Lord''s work being done in righteousness, while Acts 17:31 emphasizes judgment in righteousness by the ordained man.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 28, 66, 19, 11, 11, 'in righteousness', 'Righteous Judgment and Work', 'This connection highlights the theme of righteousness in both passages. Romans speaks of the Lord''s work being completed in righteousness, while Revelation describes the one who judges and makes war in righteousness.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 28, 19, 9, 8, 8, 'in righteousness', 'Judgment and Righteousness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine judgment and righteousness present in both passages. Romans 9:28 speaks of the Lord''s work being completed in righteousness, while Psalms 9:8 emphasizes His judgment being administered in uprightness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 28, 19, 65, 5, 5, 'cut it short in righteousness', 'Righteousness in God''s Actions', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of righteousness in God''s actions. Romans 9:28 speaks of the Lord''s work being completed in righteousness, while Psalms 65:5 mentions God''s answers coming by terrible things in righteousness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 28, 27, 9, 26, 27, 'cut it short in righteousness', 'Connection of Divine Work and Timing', 'This connection highlights the theme of a ''short work'' and the concept of being ''cut off.'' Both passages emphasize the idea of a decisive action by the Lord that has significant implications for the earth and the people.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 29, 23, 1, 9, 9, 'Except the Lord of Sabaoth had left us a seed', 'Remnant and Judgment Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a remnant saved by the Lord, preventing total destruction likened to Sodom and Gomorrah. This connection highlights the theme of divine mercy amidst impending judgment.', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 29, 23, 13, 19, 19, 'as Sodoma, and been made like unto Gomorrha', 'Destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah', 'Both passages emphasize the destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah as a significant event. Romans 9:29 references this destruction in relation to God''s mercy, while Isaiah 13:19 compares Babylon''s fate to that of Sodom and Gomorrah.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 29, 30, 4, 11, 11, 'as Sodoma, and been made like unto Gomorrha', 'Judgment and Preservation Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the judgment of God on sinful cities, specifically referencing Sodom and Gomorrah. Romans 9:29 suggests that without God''s mercy, Israel would face similar destruction, while Amos 4:11 recounts God''s judgment and the need for repentance.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 29, 59, 5, 4, 4, 'Lord of Sabaoth', 'Connection of the Lord of Sabaoth', 'Both passages emphasize the authority of the Lord of Sabaoth, highlighting His role in justice and mercy. The mention of ''Lord of Sabaoth'' in both contexts connects the themes of divine oversight and the consequences of human actions.', 'keyword', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 29, 24, 49, 18, 18, 'as Sodoma, and been made like unto Gomorrha', 'Destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah', 'Both passages emphasize the destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah, highlighting the consequences of sin. Romans 9:29 suggests that without divine intervention, Israel would face a similar fate as these cities.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 29, 24, 50, 40, 40, 'as Sodoma, and been made like unto Gomorrha', 'Destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah', 'Both passages emphasize the destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah as a warning. Romans 9:29 suggests that without divine intervention, Israel would face a similar fate, paralleling Jeremiah 50:40''s declaration of total desolation.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 29, 1, 19, 24, 25, 'as Sodoma, and been made like unto Gomorrha', 'Divine Judgment on Cities', 'Both passages emphasize the destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah as a result of divine judgment. Romans 9:29 references the fate of these cities to illustrate God''s mercy in preserving a remnant, contrasting with the total destruction described in Genesis 19:24-25.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 30, 50, 3, 9, 9, 'the righteousness which is of faith', 'Righteousness Through Faith', 'Both passages emphasize righteousness attained through faith rather than the law. Romans highlights Gentiles achieving righteousness by faith, while Philippians contrasts it with self-righteousness from the law.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 30, 58, 11, 7, 7, 'righteousness which is of faith', 'Righteousness Through Faith', 'Both passages emphasize righteousness attained through faith. Romans highlights Gentiles achieving righteousness, while Hebrews illustrates Noah''s faith leading to righteousness.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 30, 48, 2, 16, 16, 'righteousness which is of faith', 'Justification by Faith', 'Both passages emphasize that righteousness and justification come through faith rather than the works of the law. Romans highlights the Gentiles attaining righteousness through faith, while Galatians asserts that justification is not achieved by the law but through faith in Jesus Christ.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 30, 45, 4, 11, 11, 'righteousness which is of faith', 'Righteousness Through Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of righteousness being attained through faith. Romans 9:30 highlights Gentiles attaining righteousness, while Romans 4:11 discusses righteousness imputed to those who believe, regardless of circumcision.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 30, 23, 51, 1, 1, NULL, 'Righteousness and Seeking the Lord', 'This connection highlights the theme of righteousness as both passages address the pursuit of righteousness. Romans speaks of Gentiles attaining righteousness through faith, while Isaiah calls those seeking righteousness to look to their origins.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 30, 45, 9, 14, 14, NULL, 'Righteousness and God''s Justice', 'Both passages emphasize the nature of righteousness in relation to God. Romans 9:30 discusses the attainment of righteousness by the Gentiles, while Romans 9:14 questions the presence of unrighteousness with God, suggesting a connection in understanding divine justice.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 30, 48, 5, 5, 5, 'righteousness which is of faith', 'Connection of Righteousness by Faith', 'Both passages emphasize righteousness attained through faith. Romans highlights Gentiles achieving righteousness, while Galatians speaks of waiting for righteousness by faith.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 31, 45, 11, 7, 7, 'hath not attained to the law of righteousness', 'Israel''s Pursuit of Righteousness', 'Both passages emphasize Israel''s failure to attain righteousness. Romans 9:31 states that Israel has not attained to the law of righteousness, while Romans 11:7 reiterates that Israel hath not obtained that which he seeketh for.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 31, 45, 3, 20, 20, 'law of righteousness', 'Law and Righteousness Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the limitations of the law in achieving righteousness. Romans 9:31 notes Israel''s failure to attain righteousness through the law, while Romans 3:20 states that no flesh can be justified by the law. This connection highlights the theme of the law''s inability to provide true justification.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 31, 48, 5, 3, 4, 'law of righteousness', 'Law and Righteousness Connection', 'This connection highlights the struggle of Israel in attaining righteousness through the law, as noted in Romans. Similarly, Galatians emphasizes that reliance on the law for justification leads to falling from grace, indicating a failure to achieve true righteousness.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 31, 59, 2, 10, 11, 'law of righteousness', 'Law and Righteousness Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the challenge of attaining righteousness through the law. Romans highlights Israel''s failure to achieve righteousness, while James underscores that breaking any part of the law renders one guilty of all, illustrating the impossibility of perfect adherence.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 31, 23, 51, 1, 1, NULL, 'Righteousness and Seeking the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the pursuit of righteousness. Romans highlights Israel''s failure to attain righteousness, while Isaiah calls those seeking righteousness to look to the Lord. This connection highlights the theme of striving for righteousness in relation to divine guidance.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 31, 48, 3, 10, 11, 'law of righteousness', 'Law and Righteousness Connection', 'This connection highlights the struggle of Israel in attaining righteousness through the law, as noted in Romans 9:31. Galatians 3:10-11 further emphasizes that reliance on the law leads to a curse, contrasting with justification by faith.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 31, 50, 3, 6, 6, 'law of righteousness', 'Righteousness and the Law', 'Both passages emphasize the pursuit of righteousness through the law. Romans highlights Israel''s failure to attain righteousness, while Philippians presents a personal claim of blamelessness under the law.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 32, 46, 1, 23, 23, 'stumbled at that stumblingstone', 'Stumbling Block Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of Christ as a ''stumblingblock'' for both Jews and those seeking righteousness through the law. Both passages emphasize the failure to attain righteousness through works, leading to a stumbling over Christ.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 32, 42, 7, 23, 23, 'stumbled at that stumblingstone', 'Faith and Offense Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of faith and the response to Jesus. Romans discusses stumbling due to lack of faith, while Luke emphasizes the blessing for those who are not offended, suggesting a link between faith and acceptance.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 32, 45, 11, 11, 11, 'stumbled at that stumblingstone', 'Stumbling and Salvation', 'This connection highlights the theme of stumbling at the law and its consequences. Both passages emphasize how the stumbling of Israel leads to salvation for the Gentiles.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 32, 60, 2, 8, 8, 'stumblingstone', 'Stumbling Stone Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of stumbling over Christ as a ''stumblingstone'' in Romans and a ''stone of stumbling'' in 1 Peter. Both passages emphasize the disobedience of those who fail to accept the word.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 32, 40, 13, 57, 57, 'stumbled at that stumblingstone', 'Rejection of the Stumbling Stone', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of offense and rejection. In Romans, the ''stumblingstone'' represents how some fail to accept Christ by faith, while in Matthew, Jesus notes that a prophet is not honored in his own land, highlighting the rejection he faced.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 32, 42, 2, 34, 34, 'stumbled at that stumblingstone', 'Stumbling and Falling Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of stumbling and falling in both passages. Romans discusses how some stumble at the ''stumblingstone,'' while Luke mentions a child set for ''the fall and rising again'' of many.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 32, 43, 6, 27, 29, 'works of the law', 'Faith vs. Works', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of faith over works. Romans highlights the stumbling at the law, while John clarifies that belief in Jesus is the true work of God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 33, 23, 28, 16, 16, NULL, 'Connection of the Cornerstone', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of a stone laid in Zion, representing a foundation for faith. The phrase ''he that believeth shall not'' appears in both, highlighting the assurance given to believers.', 'theme', 0.643, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 33, 23, 8, 14, 15, 'rock of offence', 'Stumbling Stone Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a ''stone of stumbling'' and ''rock of offence,'' highlighting the dual role of this figure as both a sanctuary and a source of conflict. This connection illustrates the tension between belief and rejection among the people.', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 33, 45, 10, 11, 11, 'whosoever believeth on him shall not be ashamed', 'Connection of Belief and Shame', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''whosoever believeth on him shall not be ashamed,'' highlighting the assurance given to believers. This connection underscores the continuity of the message regarding faith in Christ.', 'quotation', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 33, 29, 2, 26, 27, 'shall not be ashamed', 'Connection of Shame and Belief', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of not being ashamed. Romans 9:33 states that believers will not be ashamed, while Joel 2:26-27 asserts that God''s people shall never be ashamed. This connection highlights the assurance given to those who trust in God.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 33, 60, 2, 6, 8, 'stumblingstone and rock of offence', 'Connection of the Stumbling Stone', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a ''stumblingstone'' and ''rock of offence,'' highlighting the dual nature of Christ as both a cornerstone for believers and a cause of stumbling for the disobedient. This connection illustrates the contrasting responses to Christ''s identity and message.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 33, 19, 118, 22, 22, 'stumblingstone and rock of offence', 'Connection of the Stone Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a rejected stone that becomes significant. Romans 9:33 refers to a ''stumblingstone,'' while Psalms 118:22 speaks of a ''stone which the builders refused.''', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 9, 33, 19, 25, 2, 3, 'shall not be ashamed', 'Connection of Shame and Trust', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of not being ashamed for those who trust in God. Romans 9:33 highlights that believers will not be ashamed, while Psalms 25:2-3 expresses a plea for trust that leads to the same assurance.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 1, 46, 9, 20, 22, 'that they might be saved', 'Desire for Salvation', 'Both passages emphasize the desire to save others, particularly the Jews. Romans 10:1 expresses a heartfelt prayer for Israel''s salvation, while 1 Corinthians 9:20-22 illustrates the lengths Paul goes to connect with different groups to achieve that goal.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 1, 43, 5, 34, 34, 'that they might be saved', 'Connection of Salvation Desire', 'This connection highlights the theme of salvation in both passages. Romans 10:1 expresses a desire for Israel''s salvation, while John 5:34 indicates that the speaker''s words aim for the same outcome: that ye might be saved.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 1, 45, 9, 1, 3, 'my hearts desire', 'Connection of Heartfelt Desire', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s deep concern for Israel''s salvation. The ''heart''s desire'' in Romans 10:1 reflects the ''great heaviness'' in Romans 9:2, showcasing his emotional investment in their spiritual state.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 1, 2, 32, 13, 13, 'that they might be saved', 'Desire for Israel''s Salvation', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s promise to Israel and the desire for their salvation. Both passages emphasize God''s commitment to Israel and the hope for their redemption.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 1, 24, 17, 16, 16, 'my hearts desire', 'Desire for Salvation', 'Both passages emphasize a deep desire for the well-being of others. In Romans, the desire is for Israel''s salvation, while Jeremiah expresses a commitment to his role as a pastor, indicating a concern for the people.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 1, 24, 18, 20, 20, 'that they might be saved', 'Desire for Israel''s Salvation', 'This connection highlights the theme of intercession for Israel''s salvation. Both passages express a deep concern for the fate of Israel, with Romans 10:1 showing a desire for their salvation and Jeremiah 18:20 reflecting a plea to God on their behalf.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 1, 9, 12, 23, 23, 'that they might be saved', 'Connection of Prayer for Others', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of prayer for others'' salvation and guidance. Romans 10:1 expresses a desire for Israel''s salvation, while 1 Samuel 12:23 highlights the commitment to pray for others and teach them the right way.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 2, 44, 21, 20, 20, 'zeal of God', 'Zeal for God and the Law', 'This connection highlights the shared theme of zeal for God, as seen in both passages. Romans 10:2 notes a zeal not aligned with knowledge, while Acts 21:20 describes Jews who are zealous of the law, indicating a similar fervor but differing understanding.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 2, 45, 9, 31, 32, 'zeal of God, but not according to knowledge', 'Zeal and Righteousness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of zeal without knowledge in Romans 10:2 and the failure of Israel to attain righteousness in Romans 9:31-32. Both passages emphasize the importance of faith over works, illustrating how zeal alone, without proper understanding, leads to stumbling.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 2, 20, 19, 2, 2, 'zeal of God, but not according to knowledge', 'Knowledge and Zeal Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of knowledge in relation to zeal and action. Romans highlights zeal without knowledge as misguided, while Proverbs states that lacking knowledge is not good, suggesting that both emphasize the necessity of understanding in one''s pursuits.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 2, 45, 10, 3, 3, 'zeal of God, but not according to knowledge', 'Ignorance of God''s Righteousness', 'This connection highlights the theme of zeal without knowledge. Both passages emphasize the lack of understanding regarding God''s righteousness, leading to the establishment of one''s own righteousness.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 2, 50, 1, 9, 9, 'zeal of God, but not according to knowledge', 'Knowledge and Zeal Connection', 'This connection highlights the importance of knowledge in both passages. Romans emphasizes zeal without knowledge, while Philippians prays for love to abound in knowledge.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 2, 50, 3, 6, 6, 'zeal of God', 'Connection of Zeal and Knowledge', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of zeal, with Romans noting zeal without knowledge and Philippians highlighting zeal in the context of persecuting the church. This connection highlights how zeal can manifest in different ways, particularly when not aligned with true understanding.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 2, 47, 4, 4, 4, 'zeal of God, but not according to knowledge', 'Zeal and Spiritual Blindness', 'This connection highlights the theme of misguided zeal and the inability to perceive spiritual truth. Romans 10:2 speaks of a zeal not based on knowledge, while 2 Corinthians 4:4 describes how the god of this world blinds minds, preventing the understanding of the gospel.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 3, 42, 16, 15, 15, 'righteousness of God', 'Righteousness and Justification', 'This connection highlights the theme of self-justification versus God''s righteousness. Both passages emphasize the futility of establishing one''s own righteousness in contrast to God''s standards.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 3, 50, 3, 9, 9, 'righteousness of God', 'Righteousness Through Faith', 'This connection highlights the contrast between establishing one''s own righteousness and receiving righteousness through faith in Christ. Both passages emphasize the importance of submitting to God''s righteousness rather than relying on personal efforts.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 3, 47, 5, 21, 21, 'righteousness of God', 'Righteousness of God Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''righteousness of God.'' Romans 10:3 discusses the failure to submit to God''s righteousness, while 2 Corinthians 5:21 presents the idea of being made the righteousness of God through Christ.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 3, 42, 18, 9, 12, 'establish their own righteousness', 'Righteousness and Self-Trust', 'Both passages emphasize the danger of establishing one''s own righteousness and trusting in oneself. The Pharisee in Luke exemplifies those who are ignorant of God''s righteousness, as he boasts of his own merits. This connection highlights the contrast between self-righteousness and true submission to God.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 3, 45, 1, 17, 17, 'righteousness of God', 'Righteousness of God Explained', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''righteousness of God.'' Romans 10:3 highlights the failure to submit to this righteousness, while Romans 1:17 reveals it through faith.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 3, 45, 5, 19, 19, 'righteousness of God', 'Righteousness Through Obedience', 'This connection highlights the contrast between human attempts to establish righteousness and the divine righteousness achieved through obedience. Romans 10:3 discusses ignorance of God''s righteousness, while Romans 5:19 emphasizes righteousness through the obedience of one.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 3, 66, 3, 17, 18, 'ignorant of Gods righteousness', 'Righteousness and Spiritual Poverty', 'Both passages emphasize a lack of awareness regarding true spiritual condition. Romans highlights ignorance of God''s righteousness, while Revelation addresses the Laodiceans'' self-deception about their wealth and need. This connection highlights the contrast between perceived and actual spiritual states.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 4, 48, 3, 24, 24, 'end of the law for righteousness', 'Connection Between Law and Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the role of Christ in relation to the law. Romans 10:4 states that Christ is the end of the law for righteousness, while Galatians 3:24 describes the law as a schoolmaster leading to Christ for justification by faith.', 'theme', 0.5449999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 4, 45, 8, 3, 4, 'the end of the law for righteousness', 'Connection of Law and Righteousness', 'Both passages emphasize the fulfillment of the law through Christ. Romans 10:4 states that Christ is the end of the law for righteousness, while Romans 8:4 discusses the righteousness of the law being fulfilled in those who walk after the Spirit.', 'theme', 0.496, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 4, 40, 5, 17, 18, 'Christ is the end of the law', 'Fulfillment of the Law', 'This connection highlights how Christ''s role is to fulfill the law rather than abolish it. Romans 10:4 states that Christ is the end of the law for righteousness, while Matthew 5:17 emphasizes that He came to fulfill the law.', 'theme', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 4, 44, 13, 38, 39, 'the end of the law for righteousness', 'Connection of Justification and Law', 'Both passages emphasize the role of Christ in providing righteousness and justification. Romans 10:4 states that Christ is the end of the law for righteousness, while Acts 13:39 highlights that justification comes through Him, not the law of Moses.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 4, 43, 1, 17, 17, 'the law', 'Law and Grace Contrast', 'This connection highlights the transition from law to grace. Romans 10:4 states that Christ is the end of the law, while John 1:17 emphasizes that grace and truth came by Jesus Christ.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 4, 23, 53, 11, 11, 'righteousness to every one that believeth', 'Righteousness and Justification Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of righteousness and justification found in both passages. Romans 10:4 speaks of Christ as the end of the law for righteousness, while Isaiah 53:11 refers to the righteous servant who justifies many.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 4, 58, 10, 14, 14, 'righteousness to every one that believeth', 'Connection of Righteousness and Perfection', 'This connection highlights the theme of Christ''s role in achieving righteousness and perfection for believers. Romans 10:4 speaks of Christ as the end of the law for righteousness, while Hebrews 10:14 emphasizes that through His offering, believers are perfected.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 5, 3, 18, 5, 5, 'the man which doeth those things shall live by them', 'Righteousness and Law Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the principle that adherence to the law results in life. Romans 10:5 directly echoes the idea presented in Leviticus 18:5 regarding living by the law''s statutes.', 'theme', 0.482, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 5, 16, 9, 29, 29, NULL, 'Righteousness and Law Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the principle that adherence to the law leads to life. Romans 10:5 cites the idea of living by the law, which is echoed in Nehemiah 9:29 with the phrase about living in the commandments.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 5, 26, 20, 11, 11, NULL, 'Righteousness and Living by Law', 'Both passages emphasize the principle that adherence to God''s statutes and laws is essential for life. Romans 10:5 echoes Ezekiel 20:11 by stating that doing the law leads to living by it.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 5, 26, 20, 21, 21, NULL, 'Righteousness and Law Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the principle that adherence to the law leads to life. Romans cites Moses'' description of righteousness through the law, while Ezekiel reflects on the consequences of failing to keep God''s statutes, which also includes the promise of life for those who do them.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 5, 48, 3, 12, 12, 'the man which doeth those things shall live by them', 'Connection of Righteousness and Law', 'Both passages emphasize that ''the man which doeth'' the law will live by it. This connection highlights the relationship between law and righteousness in the context of faith.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 5, 42, 10, 27, 28, NULL, 'Righteousness and Living by the Law', 'This connection highlights the theme of living by the commandments. Both passages emphasize that adherence to God''s commands leads to life, with Romans referencing the law and Luke focusing on love for God and neighbor.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 5, 45, 7, 10, 10, NULL, 'Righteousness and Commandment Connection', 'This connection highlights the contrast between the law''s intended purpose and its actual outcome. While Romans 10:5 states that righteousness comes from the law, Romans 7:10 reveals that the commandment, meant to bring life, results in death.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 6, 5, 30, 11, 14, 'Who shall ascend into heaven?', 'Connection of Righteousness and Accessibility', 'Both passages emphasize the accessibility of God''s word and righteousness. They highlight that one does not need to ascend to heaven to obtain it, as it is already near and within reach.', 'theme', 0.475, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 6, 20, 30, 4, 4, 'Who shall ascend into heaven?', 'Connection of Ascension and Righteousness', 'This connection highlights the theme of ascension in both passages. Romans 10:6 references the question of who shall ascend into heaven, paralleling Proverbs 30:4''s inquiry about who has ascended or descended.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 6, 49, 4, 8, 10, 'Who shall ascend into heaven?', 'Connection of Ascension and Descent', 'This connection highlights the themes of Christ''s descent and ascent. Romans 10:6 speaks of bringing Christ down, while Ephesians 4:8-10 discusses his ascension after descending.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 6, 43, 3, 12, 13, 'Who shall ascend into heaven?', 'Connection of Ascension and Faith', 'This connection highlights the theme of ascension and descent between heaven and earth. Both passages emphasize the idea that no one can ascend to heaven except for Christ, who came down from heaven.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 6, 43, 6, 58, 58, 'Who shall ascend into heaven?', 'Connection of Heavenly Bread', 'This connection highlights the theme of descent from heaven. Romans speaks of bringing Christ down, while John refers to the bread that came down from heaven.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 6, 45, 3, 22, 22, NULL, 'Righteousness by Faith Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of righteousness that comes through faith. Both passages emphasize that righteousness is accessible to all who believe, underscoring the universality of faith in Christ.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 6, 45, 4, 13, 13, NULL, 'Righteousness of Faith Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the righteousness of faith as central to God''s promises. Romans 10:6 discusses faith''s role in understanding Christ, while Romans 4:13 highlights faith as the means to inherit God''s promises.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 7, 58, 13, 20, 20, NULL, 'Resurrection of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus being brought back from the dead in both passages. Romans 10:7 refers to the act of bringing up Christ from the dead, while Hebrews 13:20 explicitly states that God brought again from the dead our Lord Jesus.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 7, 66, 1, 18, 18, 'bring up Christ again from the dead', 'Resurrection and Eternal Life', 'Both passages emphasize Christ''s victory over death. Romans 10:7 refers to bringing Christ up from the dead, while Revelation 1:18 declares His eternal life and authority over death.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 7, 45, 4, 25, 25, 'bring up Christ again from the dead', 'Resurrection and Justification Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the resurrection of Christ, linking His rising from the dead to the justification of believers. The phrase ''bring up Christ again from the dead'' in Romans 10:7 connects directly to His being ''raised again for our justification'' in Romans 4:25.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 7, 60, 3, 18, 18, 'bring up Christ again from the dead', 'Connection of Christ''s Resurrection', 'This connection highlights the theme of Christ''s resurrection. Both passages refer to Christ''s death and subsequent revival, emphasizing the significance of bringing believers to God.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 7, 60, 3, 22, 22, 'bring up Christ again from the dead', 'Resurrection and Ascension Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of Christ''s journey from death to exaltation. Romans 10:7 refers to bringing up Christ from the dead, while 1 Peter 3:22 speaks of His ascension to heaven and authority.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 8, 5, 30, 14, 14, NULL, 'Connection of Proximity to the Word', 'Both passages emphasize the nearness of ''the word'' in one''s mouth and heart, highlighting the accessibility of faith and obedience. This connection illustrates a continuity in the importance of internalizing God''s message.', 'theme', 0.6499999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 8, 45, 1, 16, 17, 'the word of faith, which we preach', 'Connection of Faith and Righteousness', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of faith in salvation. Romans 10:8 speaks of the ''word of faith,'' while Romans 1:16-17 highlights that the gospel reveals God''s righteousness through faith.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 8, 54, 4, 6, 6, 'word of faith', 'Connection of Faith and Doctrine', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of ''words of faith.'' Romans highlights the proximity of faith in one''s heart and mouth, while 1 Timothy encourages reminding others of these teachings as essential for good ministry.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 8, 60, 1, 25, 25, 'the word is nigh thee', 'Connection of Enduring Word', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of ''the word'' in relation to faith and the gospel. Romans highlights the immediacy of the word in one''s heart and mouth, while 1 Peter affirms the enduring nature of the word preached.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 8, 45, 10, 17, 17, 'the word of faith, which we preach', 'Connection of Faith and Hearing', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of the word in relation to faith. The ''word'' mentioned in Romans 10:8 is foundational for the faith that comes through hearing in Romans 10:17.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 8, 48, 3, 2, 2, 'the word of faith', 'Connection of Faith and Spirit', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of faith in receiving God''s promises. Romans highlights the ''word of faith,'' while Galatians questions whether the Spirit is received through faith or law.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 8, 44, 10, 43, 43, 'the word of faith, which we preach', 'Connection of Faith and Belief', 'This connection highlights the theme of faith and belief in both passages. Romans emphasizes the word of faith being in one''s heart, while Acts speaks of belief in Jesus leading to remission of sins.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 9, 42, 12, 8, 8, 'confess with thy mouth the Lord Jesus', 'Confession and Salvation Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of confessing Jesus. Romans highlights that confession leads to salvation, while Luke states that confessing Jesus before men results in acknowledgment before God.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(45, 10, 9, 44, 16, 31, 31, NULL, 'Salvation through Faith in Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize belief in the Lord Jesus for salvation. Romans 10:9 speaks of confessing Jesus and believing in His resurrection, while Acts 16:31 directly calls for belief in the Lord Jesus Christ for salvation.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
